            635.0,
            734.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "Numerous studies have been conducted on classification models [3, 31, 33, 50, 52, 63, 64], GANs [5, 19, 20, 26, 37], and others. However, due to the unique training and inference method of diffusion models, previous attack methods [64] are no longer suitable. For instance, in classification models, the model's final output is generally used as the attack feature, relying on the model's overfitting to the training data, which leads to differences in classification confidence. Additionally, previous work on generative models such as GANs focused on utilizing the discriminator for determination [37]. Since the diffusion model does not have a discriminator, which makes it different from GANs, a new attack method must be specifically designed for diffusion models.",
        "block_bbox": [
          635,
          733,
          1179,
          1024
        ],
        "block_id": 13,
        "block_order": 14,
        "group_id": 13,
        "global_block_id": 13,
        "global_group_id": 13,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            635.0,
            733.0
          ],
          [
            1179.0,
            733.0
          ],
          [
            1179.0,
            1024.0
          ],
          [
            635.0,
            1024.0
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "Some preliminary efforts have been devoted to conducting MIA on diffusion models [4, 27, 35]. However, it merits our attention that these investigations, akin to many others in this domain, predominantly concentrate on loss- and threshold-based attacks. We postulate that different layers in a neural network learn distinct features and, therefore, store varying amounts of information [65]. Evaluations based solely on loss could potentially overlook substantial information [37]. Consequently, a more comprehensive perspective of the model's response to a sample could be attained by considering gradient information from each layer post-backpropagation in addition to the loss incurred by the model.",
        "block_bbox": [
          635,
          1021,
          1175,
          1287
        ],
        "block_id": 14,
        "block_order": 15,
        "group_id": 14,
        "global_block_id": 14,
        "global_group_id": 14,
        "block_polygon_points": [
          [
            635,
            1021
          ],
          [
            635,
            1286
          ],
          [
            1168,
            1286
          ],
          [
            1174,
            1021
          ]
        ]
      },
      {
        "block_label": "text",
        "block_content": "The main challenges of utilizing gradients for MIAs are the excessive computation overhead and the overfitting issue of training the attack model (given the large size of diffusion models, gradients could have millions of dimensions). We carefully analyze ways to reduce dimensionality and propose a framework incorporating subsampling and aggregation. We call our framework Gradient attack based on Subsampling and Aggregation (GSA) and initiate",
        "block_bbox": [
          634,
          1283,
          1167,
          1458
        ],
